            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1984-12-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1984-12-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="329"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d329">
                <head>329. Personal Note Prepared by the Deputy Secretary of State (<persName
                        corresp="#p_DKW_1">Dam</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d329fn1"
                        >Source: Department of State, Executive Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_SS_1"
                            >S/S</gloss>–I Records, Deputy Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DKW_1"
                            >Dam</persName>’s Official Files: Lot 85D308, Personal Notes of Deputy
                            Secretary—<persName corresp="#p_DKW_1">Kenneth W. Dam</persName>—Oct.
                        1984–June 1985. No classification marking. Dictated by <persName
                            corresp="#p_DKW_1">Dam</persName> on December 10.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1984-12-08">December 8, 1984</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I attended several lengthy meetings today with the Secretary and our State
                    Department working group on the upcoming Geneva arms control talks. The group is
                    composed of <persName corresp="#p_NP_1">Paul Nitze</persName>, who has been
                    named as the Secretary’s special adviser and who will be attending the talks
                    with him, as well as <persName corresp="#p_AM_1">Mike Armacost</persName>,
                        <persName corresp="#p_BR_4">Rick Burt</persName>, and <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJT_1">Jack Chain</persName>. We went over several papers that
                    had been prepared, primarily by <persName corresp="#p_NP_1">Nitze</persName>, on
                    the relationship of offense and defense, which is rapidly becoming the key idea
                    behind a new approach to arms control.<note n="2" xml:id="d329fn2">For the final
                        version of <persName corresp="#p_NP_1">Nitze</persName>’s paper see <ref
                            target="#d343">Document 343</ref>.</note> The Secretary is obviously
                    trying to build on two ideas of the President’s. <pb facs="1214" n="1173"
                        xml:id="pg_1173"/> The first is that it would be desirable to do away
                    entirely with nuclear weapons. The second is that the way to get there is
                    through a strong defense, namely the <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">SDI</gloss>
                    program. These are radical ideas in view of the fact that deterrence, and
                    specifically mutual assured deterrence, has been the reigning doctrine since the
                    advent of intercontinental nuclear weapons.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to the Soviet Union.]</p>
            </div>
